# PRD Genie — AI-Powered Product Documentation Assistant

Capstone project · Applied Agentic AI for PMs/TPMs · **Shailendra Parolkar**

PRD Genie turns meeting transcripts, product briefs, and stakeholder notes into a structured PRD, epics and user stories, and the clarification questions the meeting left open — and refuses to generate a PRD when the input doesn't support one.

Built in n8n Cloud with four agents in a sequential pipeline, traced in Langfuse.

## The problem

PMs at NeuronForge spend 60–90 minutes converting each meeting into a PRD, every author formats differently, and requirements get lost between the conversation and the document. The risk that shaped this build: a PRD containing a requirement nobody stated is worse than no PRD, because engineering builds to it before anyone notices.

Six of the twelve baseline tests grade the system on *correctly refusing*. Groundedness is the design, not a feature of it.

## Architecture

```
Chat input
   ▼
Agent 1 · Requirement Extractor      gpt-4o-mini · stated / ambiguous / contradictions
   ▼
Parse + Validate                     Guardrail A — quote-or-drop, enforced in code
   ├──────────────────────────────►  Agent 4 · Gap Analyzer   gpt-4o-mini (parallel)
   ▼
Sufficiency Gate                     Guardrail B — halts when stated_count == 0
   ├── false ──► "No requirements extractable" + questions
   └── true  ──► Agent 2 · PRD Generator   gpt-4o (extraction JSON only, never the transcript)
                     ▼
                 Agent 3 · Story Breakdown  gpt-4o
                     ▼
              Merge → Langfuse → Chat response (PRD · Stories · Questions)
```

**Orchestration pattern: sequential pipeline.** Every input is the same kind of object and passes through the same fixed stages, with strict data dependencies — the PRD Generator cannot run before requirements exist. A router would classify a route already known at design time; a hierarchical planner would decompose a workflow whose decomposition is fixed. Full justification in the [architecture writeup](11-Q3-architecture-writeup.md).

### The two guardrails

**Quote-or-drop.** Every extracted requirement must carry a verbatim quote from the input. The Parse + Validate node deletes any that don't, in code, before they reach the generator — a guardrail the model can't talk its way past.

**Sufficiency gate.** When zero stated requirements are extracted, the pipeline halts and returns clarification questions. Test T9 ("Meeting happened. Notes: none.") passes by construction: the PRD Generator isn't asked to decline, it's never invoked.

The PRD template's **Source column** carries a requirement ID for every functional requirement, each resolving to a verbatim quote — so fabrication is inspectable rather than a matter of judgment.

